"# Chapter 5 — Simply Typed Lambda Calculus

Where every term wears its type, every well-typed term terminates, and
the door opens to reading types as propositions.

The untyped lambda calculus permits `(λx. (x x)) (λx. (x x))`, which loops
forever. It permits the Y combinator, which lets any function recur. It
permits terms with no clear mathematical meaning. That is expressive but
uncomfortable. What if we ruled out the pathologies by *typing*?

Types were added to the lambda calculus by Church in 1940. The system he
introduced — the *simply-typed lambda calculus*, STLC — is astonishingly
well-behaved. Every well-typed term reaches a normal form in finite time.
There is a decision procedure for typing. And, as chapter 7 will show,
STLC is *literally the same object* as a fragment of intuitionistic
propositional logic. Types are propositions; programs are proofs.

We are going to build STLC in Scheme. The syntax is the untyped lambda
calculus plus type annotations. The type-checker is a small recursive
procedure. Once it accepts a term, we know that term terminates.

## Types and terms

Types are formed from *base types* and the *arrow* type constructor.

    τ  ::=  Base                    (Bool, Nat, ...)
         |  τ → τ                   (a function from τ to τ)

Terms carry type annotations at abstraction sites.

    e  ::=  x                       (variable)
         |  c                       (constant, of some base type)
         |  (λ x : τ . e)           (typed abstraction)
         |  (e e)                   (application)

```scheme
;; type: 'Bool | 'Nat | (list 'arrow τ₁ τ₂)
;; term: symbol | number | (list 'lam symbol τ body) | (list 'app f arg)
;;
;; example:
;;   the identity function on booleans
;;   (lam x Bool x)
;;   its type: (arrow Bool Bool)
;;
;;   applying it:
;;   (app (lam x Bool x) #t)
;;   its type: Bool
```

## The typing rules

Every well-typed term is typeable by exactly one type. We write
`Γ ⊢ e : τ` to mean *in typing context Γ, the term e has type τ*. The
context Γ is a partial function from variables to types — the same
notion as the *assignment* in chapter 2.

Three rules.

**Variable.** If `Γ(x) = τ` then `Γ ⊢ x : τ`.

**Abstraction.** If `Γ, x:τ₁ ⊢ e : τ₂` then `Γ ⊢ (λx:τ₁. e) : τ₁ → τ₂`.

**Application.** If `Γ ⊢ f : τ₁ → τ₂` and `Γ ⊢ arg : τ₁` then
`Γ ⊢ (f arg) : τ₂`.

That is the whole system. Let us implement the type-checker.

```scheme
(define (lookup-type ctx var)
  (let ((pair (assq var ctx)))
    (if pair (cdr pair) (error \"unbound variable\" var))))

(define (type-of term ctx)
  (cond
    ((symbol? term)                                 ; variable
     (lookup-type ctx term))
    ((number? term) 'Nat)                           ; primitive constant
    ((boolean? term) 'Bool)
    ((eq? (car term) 'lam)
     (let* ((param     (cadr term))
            (param-ty  (caddr term))
            (body      (cadddr term))
            (body-ty   (type-of body (cons (cons param param-ty) ctx))))
       (list 'arrow param-ty body-ty)))
    ((eq? (car term) 'app)
     (let* ((fn       (cadr term))
            (arg      (caddr term))
            (fn-ty    (type-of fn ctx))
            (arg-ty   (type-of arg ctx)))
       (cond
         ((not (and (pair? fn-ty) (eq? (car fn-ty) 'arrow)))
          (error \"applying non-function\" fn fn-ty))
         ((not (equal? (cadr fn-ty) arg-ty))
          (error \"argument type mismatch\"
                 (list :expected (cadr fn-ty) :got arg-ty)))
         (else
          (caddr fn-ty)))))))
```

Run it:

```scheme
(type-of '(lam x Bool x) '())
;; => (arrow Bool Bool)

(type-of '(app (lam x Bool x) #t) '())
;; => Bool

(type-of '(app (lam x Bool x) 5) '())
;; => error: argument type mismatch, expected Bool, got Nat
```

Three cases, one function. Every term either type-checks (and its type
is returned) or fails to type-check with an error indicating where.

## What Ω looks like in STLC

Consider the pathological `(λx. (x x))`. In untyped lambda calculus this
is fine. In STLC, what type could `x` have?

- `x` is applied to itself, so `x` must have a function type: `τ → τ'`.
- The argument is `x` itself, so `x` must also have type `τ`.
- We need `τ = τ → τ'`. A type equal to a function type containing
  itself. There is no finite type that satisfies this.

So `(λx. (x x))` is not typeable in STLC. Ω cannot be written. This is
the *fundamental restriction* of STLC: self-application is forbidden
because it demands infinite types.

Some type systems (recursive types, System F ω) do allow such
self-referential types back in, and get back the full power of untyped
lambda calculus, but STLC does not. In STLC every well-typed term
terminates.

## Strong normalization

The theorem is called *strong normalization*: for STLC, every reduction
sequence starting from a well-typed term terminates in a normal form.

The proof (Tait, 1967; simplified using *logical relations*) is technical
and beautiful — one of the classic pieces of proof theory. We will not
work through it here; Girard-Lafont-Taylor chapter 6 is the classic
presentation. But the *statement* is what matters. It says: STLC is a
programming language in which every program halts.

That sounds like a bug. It rules out any interesting programming, right?
No general recursion, no infinite loops, no interactive processes. What
kind of language is that?

The answer: STLC is not a general-purpose programming language. It is a
*proof language*. Every well-typed term is a proof of the proposition
its type encodes (chapter 7 will unpack this). If you want general
recursion, you have to add it — and *system with recursion* has been the
name of a research programme since the 1970s.

The languages Coq, Agda, and Lean are the modern descendants. They add
carefully-controlled forms of recursion — *well-founded* recursion,
structural recursion, guarded recursion — that preserve termination
while permitting most useful computations. This is why those languages
can be used both to write programs *and* to prove theorems.

## Type inference

We wrote `type-of`, which computes a term's type given full type
annotations. Real languages let you *omit* the annotations and infer
them. This is what ML and Haskell do.

Type inference for STLC is decidable and has a beautiful algorithm:
*Hindley-Milner*, discovered independently by Hindley (1969) and Milner
(1978). The algorithm has three moves:

1. Assign a fresh type variable to every unannotated bound variable.
2. Walk the term generating type *constraints*: at every application,
   constrain the function's argument type to match the actual argument
   type.
3. Solve the constraints by *unification*: find a substitution that
   makes them all true.

Unification is a small algorithm in its own right (Appendix B). Here is
the shape of the constraint generator.

```scheme
(define type-var-counter 0)
(define (fresh-tyvar!)
  (set! type-var-counter (+ type-var-counter 1))
  (list 'tvar type-var-counter))

(define (infer term ctx)
  ;; Returns (list :type <ty> :constraints <constraints>)
  (cond
    ((symbol? term)
     (let ((ty (lookup-type ctx term)))
       (list :type ty :constraints '())))
    ((eq? (car term) 'lam)
     ;; unannotated lambda: (lam x body)
     (let* ((param    (cadr term))
            (body     (caddr term))
            (param-ty (fresh-tyvar!))
            (body-r   (infer body
                             (cons (cons param param-ty) ctx))))
       (list :type (list 'arrow param-ty (get :type body-r))
             :constraints (get :constraints body-r))))
    ((eq? (car term) 'app)
     (let* ((fn-r   (infer (cadr term) ctx))
            (arg-r  (infer (caddr term) ctx))
            (result-ty (fresh-tyvar!))
            (new-c  (list (list (get :type fn-r)
                                'equals
                                (list 'arrow (get :type arg-r)
                                             result-ty)))))
       (list :type result-ty
             :constraints (append (get :constraints fn-r)
                                  (get :constraints arg-r)
                                  new-c))))))
```

`(get key alist)` looks up a key. After running `infer`, we hand the
constraint list to a unifier which either solves them (producing a
substitution to apply to the type) or fails (producing a type error
message pointing at the conflict).

The full unifier is in Appendix B. It follows Robinson's original 1965
algorithm, augmented with the *occurs check* that prevents infinite
types like `τ = τ → τ`.

## An example

Consider:

    (λf. (λx. (f x)))

What is its type in STLC? Without annotations, we start by giving `f`
type `α` (a fresh variable) and `x` type `β`. The body `(f x)` requires
`f`'s type to be `β → γ` for some `γ`. So `α = β → γ`. The abstraction
`(λx. (f x))` has type `β → γ`. The outer abstraction `(λf. ...)` has
type `α → (β → γ)`, i.e., `(β → γ) → (β → γ)`. So this term's
most general type is `(β → γ) → (β → γ)`.

Read that. *For any β and γ, this term takes a function from β to γ and
returns a function from β to γ.* It is the identity function on
functions — well, it is eta-equivalent to `f`, which is the identity on
functions. Hindley-Milner discovers this without our help.

Note the free variables in the type. In ML, these get *universally
quantified* at the `let`-binding, giving what is called a *type scheme*:

    ∀β γ. (β → γ) → (β → γ)

This is called *let-polymorphism* and it is the small taste of
polymorphism you get in the simply-typed calculus with `let`. Full
polymorphism — where you can `∀`-quantify anywhere — is System F, which
we will meet in chapter 6.

## Extensions

STLC is minimal. A real language adds product types, sum types, unit
type, base types (Bool, Nat, String), and general recursion.

**Product types.**

    (τ₁ × τ₂)     (pair, fst, snd)

Typing rules:
- If `Γ ⊢ e₁ : τ₁` and `Γ ⊢ e₂ : τ₂` then `Γ ⊢ (pair e₁ e₂) : τ₁ × τ₂`.
- If `Γ ⊢ e : τ₁ × τ₂` then `Γ ⊢ (fst e) : τ₁` and `Γ ⊢ (snd e) : τ₂`.

**Sum types.**

    (τ₁ + τ₂)     (inl, inr, case)

Typing rules:
- If `Γ ⊢ e : τ₁` then `Γ ⊢ (inl e) : τ₁ + τ₂` for any τ₂.
- Case-analysis: `(case e (inl x -> e₁) (inr y -> e₂))` requires
  `Γ ⊢ e : τ₁ + τ₂`, `Γ, x:τ₁ ⊢ e₁ : τ`, `Γ, y:τ₂ ⊢ e₂ : τ`, and
  produces τ.

**Unit type.**

    Unit           ((), the trivial value)

One value: `()`. This becomes surprisingly important in chapter 7.

Each of these has a proof-theoretic analogue that we will meet again
in chapters 7 and 8. Products are conjunctions. Sums are disjunctions.
Unit is truth (⊤). Absurd (bottom, no values) is falsity (⊥). The
*rules* for each type constructor mirror the introduction and
elimination rules for the corresponding logical connective. That is
Curry-Howard, and we are approaching it deliberately.

## Beta reduction with types

The reduction rule is the same as untyped, with one bonus: reduction
*preserves types*. If `Γ ⊢ e : τ` and `e → e'`, then `Γ ⊢ e' : τ`.
This is called *subject reduction* or *preservation*.

Together with *progress* (every well-typed non-value can take a step),
preservation gives you what Pierce's textbook calls the *proof of type
safety*. A well-typed program never gets stuck, never encounters a
runtime type error. Types are checked once, at compile time; the
runtime is free of type dispatch.

```scheme
;; Sketch of a proof that reduction preserves types.
;; For each reduction rule:
;;   (app (lam x t body) arg)  →  body[x := arg]
;; If the redex has type τ, then:
;;   fn has type (arrow τ_arg τ)
;;   arg has type τ_arg
;;   body has type τ under context extended with (x . τ_arg)
;;   substituting arg for x preserves type — by a substitution lemma.
```

The *substitution lemma* is a small technical result: substituting a
term for a variable does not change the resulting term's type, provided
the substituted term has the variable's declared type. It is proved by
induction on the structure of the body being substituted into. Pierce
chapter 9 proves it in full.

## When STLC is enough

Because STLC has no general recursion, it cannot express Turing-complete
computation. But it can express plenty of interesting computation.

- Every polynomial function on natural numbers is expressible.
- All primitive-recursive functions (once you add specific recursion
  combinators like `foldNat`) are expressible in the *extended* STLC
  called *Godel's System T*.
- Boolean logic, choice, conditionals, sums and products, and their
  compositions.

For most *terminating* algorithms of the sort you find in a data
structures textbook — searching, sorting, tree traversals — STLC-with-
foldNat suffices. Where it does not suffice is anywhere you need
open-ended recursion: reading input, iterative refinement, interactive
processes.

The right way to think about STLC: it is the *terminating fragment* of
computation. When you want that fragment (proof checking, type checking,
compilation), STLC is your friend. When you want more, you add recursion
back explicitly and knowingly.

## Variations to try

Extend the type-checker with product types and sum types. This roughly
doubles the size of the checker, and it makes it dramatically more
useful. Try writing a small function that takes a `Nat + Nat` and
returns a `Nat` (the value inside, whichever tag). Watch the case
expression grow into an actual conditional.

Implement Hindley-Milner in full: constraint generation, unification
with occurs check, generalization at `let`. This is one of the great
compact algorithms of computer science. The whole thing fits in about
150 lines of Scheme.

Add primitive numeric types and try to type-check a small program:
factorial (which will fail — no recursion), pair-swap (which will
succeed), map-over-a-list (which will succeed once you add lists as a
built-in). Notice which programs fit and which do not.

## Try this

Write, in STLC, the *composition* function `(λf. (λg. (λx. (f (g x)))))`.
Type-check it. You will find its most general type is
`(β → γ) → (α → β) → (α → γ)`. Read that aloud: *composition is
polymorphic in three type variables and produces a function equivalent
to `f ∘ g`.* Now consider what this same term is doing on the propositional
side: if you read arrows as implications, this term is a proof of
`(β → γ) → (α → β) → (α → γ)`, which is *hypothetical syllogism*. Same
term, two readings. That is a preview of chapter 7.

## Closing

We added types. In exchange, the calculus became well-behaved: every
term terminates, type-checking is decidable, type inference works.
The cost is expressiveness — we lost the Y combinator and any form of
general recursion. That cost is what we pay for the guarantee that our
programs terminate.

Chapter 6 loosens the type system in a different direction: polymorphism.
We keep termination; we regain the ability to write functions like `map`
and `filter` that work over any type. And we discover that polymorphism
alone is enough to encode data types like natural numbers, pairs, and
lists — all without primitives. That is System F, and it is a jewel.
"
